
1.   What is map() array method?  How to use  map() method in javascript?   

The map() method in JavaScript is an array function that creates a new array populated with the results of calling a provided function on every element in the original array. It is commonly used for transforming or processing array elements without altering the original array.

const newArray = array.map(callback(currentValue, index, array), thisArg);


2.   What are other usages of spread operator (...) in JavaScript?

	•	Copying arrays
	•	Merging arrays
	•	Adding elements to arrays
	•	Converting a string to an array of characters
	•	Copying and merging objects
	•	Passing array elements as function arguments



// Copying Arrays


const originalArray = [1, 2, 3];
const copiedArray = [...originalArray];
console.log("Copied Array:", copiedArray); // Output: [1, 2, 3]

// Merging Arrays
const array1 = [1, 2];
const array2 = [3, 4];
console.log("Combined Array:", combinedArray); // Output: [1, 2, 3, 4]

// Adding Elements to Arrays
const numbers = [2, 3];
const withNewElement = [1, ...numbers, 4];
console.log("Array with New Elements:", withNewElement); // Output: [1, 2, 3, 4]

// Converting a String to an Array of Characters
const word = "hello";
const letters = [...word];
console.log("String to Array of Characters:", letters); // Output: ['h', 'e', 'l', 'l', 'o']

// Copying and Merging Objects
const person = { name: "Alice", age: 25 };
const updatedPerson = { ...person, age: 26 };
console.log("Updated Person Object:", updatedPerson); // Output: { name: "Alice", age: 26 }

// Passing Array Elements as Function Arguments
const nums = [1, 2, 3];
function add(a, b, c) {
    return a + b + c;
}
console.log("Sum of Array Elements:", add(...nums)); // Output: 6



